SIMPLE: efflux
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Efflux
<hw>Ef"flux</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Effluent</er>, <er>Flux</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or
process of flowing out, or issuing forth; effusion; outflow; <as>as, the
<ex>efflux</ex> of matter from an ulcer; the <ex>efflux</ex> of men's
piety.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is then that the devout affections . . . are incessantly in
<qex>efflux</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which flows out; emanation;
effluence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prime cheerer, light! . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Efflux</qex> divine.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Efflux</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Efflux
<hw>Ef*flux"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To run out; to
flow forth; to pass away.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effluxion</ent>⟦br⟧
